# Application of the Supply Chain Enablement Program

## Overview

This document describes how the Supply Chain Enablement Program would be applied within an academic medical center environment. The framework is designed to support standardized education, system adoption, and continuous process improvement across a complex, cross-functional healthcare supply chain.

The program positions education and training as a strategic capabilityâ€”supporting operational readiness, compliance, and measurable performance outcomes rather than functioning as standalone or ad hoc training.

---

## Role-Based Onboarding and Readiness

The program supports new Supply Chain staff through structured, role-based onboarding using 30-60-90 day readiness paths. These learning paths are designed to reduce time-to-proficiency by standardizing foundational knowledge, system usage, policy awareness, and workflow expectations across procurement, receiving, inventory, and accounts payable functions.

This approach reduces onboarding variability, reinforces compliance from day one, and ensures consistent operational readiness across teams and sites.

---

## Cross-Functional Training and Knowledge Continuity

Beyond onboarding, the program enables cross-functional training focused on key handoff points between Supply Chain, Information Resources (IR), Finance, and end-user departments. Training modules and reference materials address common breakdown areas such as:

- eProcurement request-to-receipt workflows  
- Receiving discrepancies and inventory adjustments  
- Accounts Payable handoffs and issue resolution  
- IR-supported system workflows impacting Supply Chain operations  

By improving shared understanding across functions, the program helps reduce rework, delays, and downstream errors that commonly occur in healthcare supply chains.

---

## System Change Readiness and Adoption Support

For system enhancements, integrations, or new functionality, the program serves as the Supply Chain change enablement and user readiness function.

This includes:
- Change impact assessments  
- Go-live readiness checklists  
- Train-the-trainer models  
- User communications and job aids  
- Post-go-live adoption and support metrics  

This structured approach supports smoother system launches, improves user confidence, and reduces post-implementation disruption and support ticket volume.

---

## Metrics, KPIs, and Leadership Visibility

The program supports leadership through defined KPIs and outcome-based reporting that connect training and adoption efforts to measurable operational results.

Example metrics include:
- Training completion and certification rates  
- Time-to-proficiency for new hires  
- Error rate and rework trends  
- Cycle time improvements for key workflows  
- System adoption and utilization metrics post-go-live  

These insights enable data-driven decision making, reinforce accountability, and support continuous improvement initiatives.

---

## Scalability and Institutional Alignment

This framework is designed to scale with the size and complexity of an academic medical center. It aligns with institutional policies, compliance requirements, and IR partnerships while supporting a culture of standardized best practices, operational excellence, and continuous learning across the Supply Chain organization.

The model is intentionally modular, allowing leadership to prioritize high-impact workflows while maintaining consistent governance and operating structure.
